WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Please join me in welcoming Sharla Gelfand.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:17.360
Hi everyone, thanks for coming.

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:19.240
I am so excited to be here.

00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:24.360
RStudioConf is my favorite thing in the world, pretty much, and it took me quite a trajectory

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:25.360
to get here.

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:29.959
So, three years ago, I came to RStudioConf for the first time, and I lost my wallet and

00:00:29.959 --> 00:00:33.480
Joe Chang had to lend me money to get home.

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:37.959
And now, I'm here talking, so if anyone has lost their wallet, cancel your credit cards

00:00:37.959 --> 00:00:42.040
and please submit a talk abstract in 2023.

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:46.480
So I'm here to talk to you about repeated reporting in the R universe.

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:52.560
If you're interested in the slides, they are available at bit.ly slash rstudioconf, and

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:57.400
you may know me on Twitter as Sharla Gelfand, and if not, please follow me.

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:01.480
So the inspiration for this talk came from my previous job, where I was a statistician

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:06.199
working with data on Ontario's nursing workforce, and at this job, we had a set of reports that

00:01:06.199 --> 00:01:10.440
we had to write every year, released to the government, and these reports used to be written

00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:16.120
using a combination of SPSS, Excel, and Word, with a lot of decisions kept track of in email

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:17.480
and paper notes.

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:21.480
The process was pretty manual, and it might sound familiar to some of you.

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:23.839
So first, we would somehow acquire the data.

00:01:23.839 --> 00:01:27.980
In a lot of cases, this involved emailing someone from the IT team, waiting for them

00:01:27.980 --> 00:01:32.839
to have time to work on the project, then they would query the data and send it to us.

00:01:32.839 --> 00:01:37.400
Then we use SPSS to clean and explore the data and make some summary tables.

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:42.760
We move over to Excel, where there are nicely formatted tables, move the data over a year,

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:44.220
and paste the new data in.

00:01:44.220 --> 00:01:48.720
Then we go to Word and replace the tables, change some numbers and text.

00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:52.919
Then we discover that there's a mistake in the data in the report.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.199
So we go back and we do everything all over again.

00:01:56.199 --> 00:01:58.279
This might sound familiar to some of you.

00:01:58.279 --> 00:02:03.080
So these reports, which we had to write every year, took all year.

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:07.599
They weren't reproducible, and things were scattered, hard to keep track of, and the

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:11.880
work was boring, manual, and repetitive, and not easily repeatable.

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:15.399
And instead of being able to do new things on the job, we were stuck doing the same work

00:02:15.399 --> 00:02:17.960
over and over again.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:21.240
So this is a bit of a spoiler, but I'm sure you knew that this was going.

00:02:21.279 --> 00:02:24.279
So first, I have to say that I have not been completely honest.

00:02:24.279 --> 00:02:26.880
I didn't do any of the previous work.

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:31.199
My coworker, Charlene, who is here, and previous statisticians did this, but I started the

00:02:31.199 --> 00:02:34.960
job knowing that I had no interest in using SPSS.

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:40.119
So I started the job, I took about a week to understand how things were going, how we

00:02:40.119 --> 00:02:45.119
made these reports, and I was having lunch with my coworker, and I'm like, hey, have

00:02:45.119 --> 00:02:46.119
you heard of R?

00:02:46.119 --> 00:02:47.119
It took a week.

00:02:47.119 --> 00:02:50.479
You know, settle in.

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:52.759
And she had, thank God.

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:56.880
So Charlene had used R in grad school and was more than happy to have opportunities

00:02:56.880 --> 00:02:58.100
to use it more.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:01.960
She had wanted to improve our processes, so she quickly learned the tidyverse, fell right

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:06.880
into the pit of success, and we transitioned all of our projects over to R.

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:11.240
So we got the queries from our database team, we learned about our database structure, and

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:15.839
we used packages like dplyr and dbplyr to query them.

00:03:15.839 --> 00:03:22.279
Then we used tidier, janitor, and other tidyverse packages to clean our data, and we used R markdown,

00:03:22.279 --> 00:03:25.479
cable extra, and ggplot2 to write our reports.

00:03:25.479 --> 00:03:30.160
And everything fit so well, almost as if it was designed to work together, and pretty

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:37.199
soon our workflow started looking a lot like my laptop.

00:03:37.199 --> 00:03:39.479
We were so proud of what we had accomplished.

00:03:39.479 --> 00:03:44.020
Our code was reproducible, and we didn't have to redo everything if there was a mistake.

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:47.619
Our code was all in one place and easier to keep track of, and it took a little bit

00:03:47.619 --> 00:03:51.220
of time to transition things, but we knew it would be worth it because we had time to

00:03:51.220 --> 00:03:53.500
do new things on the job.

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:57.539
And next year arrives, and considering that there's 15 minutes left in this talk, I'm

00:03:57.539 --> 00:04:00.059
guessing you can tell that things did not go as expected.

00:04:00.059 --> 00:04:05.699
But, you know, I was feeling good, I go to work on these projects next year, and as an

00:04:05.699 --> 00:04:08.940
obsessed R user, I was like, there's nothing that can go wrong.

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:11.759
We're using R, it's foolproof, we're all good.

00:04:11.759 --> 00:04:15.320
And then I would come back to projects, just ready to knock them off to the to-do list,

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:17.640
and see something that looks like this.

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:23.119
So I come back to my code, and I'm like, okay, so we got check demographic assumptions done,

00:04:23.119 --> 00:04:28.760
check demographics, old code, then we have, you know, demographics report, copy of demographics

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:35.399
report, we've got try cleaning demographics again, untitled.R.

00:04:35.399 --> 00:04:39.880
And so I'm like, yeah, I'm a pretty organized person, but I come back to this, and I have

00:04:39.880 --> 00:04:41.880
just no idea where to start.

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:46.399
Things are not named clearly, it is a jumbled mess, and I don't know what files are what,

00:04:46.399 --> 00:04:49.200
what order to do them in, and what's usable or what's old.

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:52.200
So I'm like, okay, you know, this one says done, so that's probably a pretty good candidate

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:53.559
to open it.

00:04:53.559 --> 00:05:00.000
So I open the code, and so I take the data, and I'm like, okay, so I change the value

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:01.760
of a field for one ID, why?

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:02.760
I don't know.

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:07.200
And the value of a different field for a different ID, again, I have no idea why.

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:10.399
And then I take the data, I filter it, and I do some aggregation.

00:05:10.399 --> 00:05:12.480
And at this point, I'm like, cool, cool, cool, cool.

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:16.600
So I have just no idea what is going on here.

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:20.839
Because the code that I was writing was, like, so specific for last year's project, and I

00:05:20.839 --> 00:05:23.239
wasn't thinking about how to reuse this code.

00:05:23.239 --> 00:05:27.359
So it was salvageable, you know, I have to go through, I remember what's what, I copy

00:05:27.359 --> 00:05:32.880
files over, I change filters, but I was so frustrated, because we had stopped using SPSS,

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:36.200
Excel, and Word, because things were not reproducible.

00:05:36.200 --> 00:05:40.600
They were difficult to keep track of, manual and repetitive, not easily repeatable, and

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:42.040
time-consuming.

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:46.920
But the way that I was leaving my R code, things were kind of reproducible, difficult

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:51.760
to keep track of, manual and repetitive, not easily repeatable, and time-consuming.

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:53.799
I think you all got it, but it's, like, the same list.

00:05:53.799 --> 00:06:00.399
Do you want me to explain all the jokes?

00:06:00.399 --> 00:06:05.640
So in order to avoid having this happen again, I developed a set of approaches guided by

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:09.760
two principles, don't repeat yourself and talk to yourself.

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:15.420
And I hope that it's useful for those of you who use R for this kind of repetitive reporting.

00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:20.600
So don't repeat yourself is a concept from software engineering aimed at reducing repetition.

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:25.760
It says that you should abstract away repetitive logic and automate repetitive processes.

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:27.440
So why do we want to do this?

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:31.519
Well, copy and pasting your code is really error-prone, and you have to make an update

00:06:31.519 --> 00:06:33.459
everywhere that the code appears.

00:06:33.459 --> 00:06:39.100
And instead of focusing on what changes, we're busy focusing on what stays the same.

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:42.619
You've probably all heard the mantra that if you copy and paste the same code three

00:06:42.619 --> 00:06:44.820
times, you should turn it into a function.

00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:49.739
So functions and packages are really the core of don't repeat yourself in the R universe.

00:06:49.739 --> 00:06:53.260
But repetition is also present in processes.

00:06:53.260 --> 00:06:58.660
Having to redo things, remember where things are, remember what you did is pretty pointless,

00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:01.660
and you might not be able to abstract away that process, but you can definitely try to

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:03.899
automate things.

00:07:03.899 --> 00:07:09.700
Talk to yourself is a concept from me that I thought sounded good with don't repeat yourself.

00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:13.140
And it basically is just aimed at making work easier to use for your future self.

00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:17.540
So it's way easier to document why you're doing something now than to remember why you

00:07:17.540 --> 00:07:19.100
did it a year ago.

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:24.100
The goal here is to focus on your future self instead of your present self, and just because

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:27.859
we write easy-to-read code because of the tidyverse doesn't mean that it actually explains

00:07:27.859 --> 00:07:31.820
the motivations of why we're doing something.

00:07:31.820 --> 00:07:36.339
So with these principles, the first thing I did is I cleaned up after myself.

00:07:36.339 --> 00:07:40.559
And I needed to do this because my old code was just not reusable, and there was so much

00:07:40.559 --> 00:07:45.579
repetition of process having to relearn where things were, what they did, and what to do.

00:07:45.579 --> 00:07:49.679
So you've seen this before, and I think we can agree that leaving files like this is

00:07:49.679 --> 00:07:50.679
just rude.

00:07:50.679 --> 00:07:53.220
Like, nobody wants that.

00:07:53.220 --> 00:07:58.940
So the first thing I did to reorganize that is I separated out data, reference code, and

00:07:58.940 --> 00:08:03.940
old code and reorganized things and named them clearly to communicate what they're actually

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:04.940
doing.

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:09.660
I also took advantage of the default ordering, which does things by name, and gave numbers

00:08:09.660 --> 00:08:11.880
to indicate what order things happen in.

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:15.440
And even if this is all you do, next year when you come back, you can just copy the

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:20.179
old code over and go through things in order.

00:08:20.179 --> 00:08:24.619
But in case things were not obvious enough from the order, I also started creating this

00:08:24.619 --> 00:08:29.140
setup file, which is really useful for starting a project, like having a readme or an introductory

00:08:29.140 --> 00:08:31.220
vignette when using a new package.

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:34.619
This is a good place to explain the project, where to start, like if you have to email

00:08:34.619 --> 00:08:36.539
someone and what steps to take.

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:40.380
And the goal here is to explain how to do something and why to do something instead

00:08:40.380 --> 00:08:43.359
of just leaving an artifact of what you already did.

00:08:43.359 --> 00:08:48.020
So this one's pretty basic, but it's, hello, welcome to the annual demographics report.

00:08:48.020 --> 00:08:51.539
Step one, query the data, open the file, and run the code.

00:08:51.539 --> 00:08:56.140
Step two, clean the data, open the file, and run the code.

00:08:56.140 --> 00:09:00.099
And once I left my files usable as a whole, I had to start thinking about them individually

00:09:00.099 --> 00:09:04.099
and how I could make going through things less manually repetitive and what to abstract

00:09:04.099 --> 00:09:05.099
away.

00:09:05.099 --> 00:09:07.380
So functions are a great way to do this.

00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:12.140
So I had some code to clean and query data that was a good candidate for this.

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:16.580
So if we look at this code, we have a long and complicated SQL query or a dplyr version

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:17.580
of it.

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:20.719
Then you filter the data where the year is 2019.

00:09:20.719 --> 00:09:25.140
You have a bunch of code to rename and select columns, 30 various lines to clean up and

00:09:25.140 --> 00:09:28.340
summarize the data, and some more code to save the data.

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:31.760
So I mean, talking through this is boring, and I like to talk.

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:35.580
So you definitely don't want to have to run through this code every time you do it.

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:39.239
And the thing with this code is that everything stays the same, and the only thing that changes

00:09:39.239 --> 00:09:40.500
is the year.

00:09:40.500 --> 00:09:45.359
So it's a really good set of code to turn into a function where you take what stays

00:09:45.359 --> 00:09:49.520
the same, make it into the body of the function, and then you take what changes and make it

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:51.440
into the argument of the function.

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:55.239
Then you don't have to run through this code, copy it, or update logic in multiple places

00:09:55.239 --> 00:09:58.119
if it changes.

00:09:58.119 --> 00:10:02.559
I also put this function into the setup file so that you can just run the function and

00:10:02.559 --> 00:10:07.880
have it query the data rather than saying go and open 01 queried data.

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:12.159
But abstraction was not enough for me, so I also decided to make my functions chatty

00:10:12.159 --> 00:10:15.080
as an opportunity to talk to myself.

00:10:15.799 --> 00:10:19.400
So the use this package is amazing for many, many things, but I like this obscure part

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:23.359
where you can just print UI to your console.

00:10:23.359 --> 00:10:29.479
So if you do UI info and you say hi, it'll print a little I for info and hi to the console,

00:10:29.479 --> 00:10:32.559
and you can use this in your own functions to print different kinds of output to the

00:10:32.559 --> 00:10:33.960
console.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:35.919
You can also use code in these functions.

00:10:35.919 --> 00:10:41.960
So if I set the analysis year to 2019 and I do UI to do in this case, I can do querying

00:10:42.039 --> 00:10:47.559
demographics data for analysis year, and it'll print querying demographics data for 2019

00:10:47.559 --> 00:10:48.559
in the function.

00:10:48.559 --> 00:10:54.320
So at the end, I had a function that when I ran it, it actually helped me keep track

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:55.659
of what was going on.

00:10:55.659 --> 00:11:00.039
So you run it and it says querying demographics data for 2019, and then it tells you where

00:11:00.039 --> 00:11:01.039
it's saved.

00:11:01.039 --> 00:11:04.159
Because if you're coming back to this project a year later, you don't really need to track

00:11:04.159 --> 00:11:05.159
those things down.

00:11:05.159 --> 00:11:07.880
It'll just tell you.

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:12.559
So I knew that not all of my code had logic that could abstract it away.

00:11:12.559 --> 00:11:14.919
Our projects had a lot of really specific data cleaning steps.

00:11:14.919 --> 00:11:18.599
There was a lot of back and forth and a lot of checking of assumptions and always some

00:11:18.599 --> 00:11:21.840
level of human interaction required.

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:26.679
But a big lesson that I learned is that artisanal data does not require artisanal code.

00:11:26.679 --> 00:11:32.919
So we had very special data, like locally sourced, handcrafted, new mistakes daily artisanal

00:11:32.919 --> 00:11:35.239
data.

00:11:35.239 --> 00:11:39.440
But the mistake that I always made was that I was so focused on cleaning that set of data,

00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:42.719
and I wasn't thinking about how to clean a new batch of the data.

00:11:42.719 --> 00:11:47.400
And I only knew why I had done something last time and not what to look for this time.

00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:51.719
So instead of writing super specific code, I started writing generalizable code with

00:11:51.719 --> 00:11:56.840
super specific instructions, including things on data cleaning, who to ask, what to look

00:11:56.840 --> 00:11:58.400
for and what to do.

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:01.599
And this actually gives you time to deal with cleaning your artisanal data because you're

00:12:01.599 --> 00:12:05.799
not wasting time remembering how to clean it.

00:12:05.799 --> 00:12:07.000
So we've seen this before.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.400
But again, what my code used to look like is that I would take the data, change the

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:14.200
value of a field for one ID and the value of a different field for a different ID with

00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:16.200
no idea why I had done it.

00:12:16.200 --> 00:12:18.559
But what I replaced it with is something that looks like this.

00:12:18.559 --> 00:12:20.200
So first I'm saying what to do.

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:25.719
So an example is I want to check for any cases where the province is Ontario, but outside

00:12:25.719 --> 00:12:29.780
of Ontario is true, because that's obviously not right.

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:30.780
And then why to do it?

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:34.659
Because some of them may have province wrong, but some may have outside Ontario wrong.

00:12:34.659 --> 00:12:36.659
And then you say who to talk to.

00:12:36.659 --> 00:12:37.659
So email Carla.

00:12:37.659 --> 00:12:38.659
I made up a name.

00:12:38.659 --> 00:12:39.659
Sounds like my name.

00:12:39.659 --> 00:12:41.340
It's close enough.

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:45.859
And ask them to check paper files to confirm which is correct and then what to do next.

00:12:45.859 --> 00:12:50.780
So based on the response, update any manually until the database is updated.

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:54.739
Because when I started this job, I found it so difficult to keep track of who to ask for

00:12:54.739 --> 00:12:55.739
different things.

00:12:55.739 --> 00:12:58.539
You know, like you have to email that person and if they're gone, you have to email someone

00:12:58.539 --> 00:12:59.539
else.

00:13:00.299 --> 00:13:04.340
So I decided to just codify it so I wasn't leaving myself wondering.

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:08.260
And then to avoid repetition, I could write a function that actually automates producing

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:11.340
the template, again, using the use this package.

00:13:11.340 --> 00:13:17.419
So you take the template, it makes and saves a copy of it, and you can even pass data to

00:13:17.419 --> 00:13:19.260
it.

00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:22.219
And finally, I put everything together into a package.

00:13:22.219 --> 00:13:26.219
A project like this is a great candidate for making a package, and it is not as scary as

00:13:26.219 --> 00:13:27.299
it seems.

00:13:27.380 --> 00:13:31.099
And once I started making packages for this, I started making packages for everything else

00:13:31.099 --> 00:13:34.659
in my life.

00:13:34.659 --> 00:13:35.659
No further details.

00:13:35.659 --> 00:13:40.299
So why do we want to make a package?

00:13:40.299 --> 00:13:45.299
I mean, as I said, making a package is really an ultimate form of do not repeat yourself.

00:13:45.299 --> 00:13:49.299
Your functions are centralized in a specific place and it's really clear where to update

00:13:49.299 --> 00:13:50.299
them.

00:13:50.299 --> 00:13:53.820
Your templates also have a place to live and then you can use other functions to copy and

00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:55.419
pass data to them.

00:13:55.419 --> 00:13:59.140
There's robust documentation and you can share code with your coworkers in a better way than

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:02.380
emailing it or having it on a network drive.

00:14:02.380 --> 00:14:06.059
So when all was said and done, I had a package that looked something like this.

00:14:06.059 --> 00:14:12.700
So my functions had a home in the R directory, and then the templates live in a special place

00:14:12.700 --> 00:14:15.219
so you can copy and use them later.

00:14:15.219 --> 00:14:19.700
There's documentation in the form of a readme, function documentation in the man folder,

00:14:19.700 --> 00:14:21.940
and vignettes for detailed usage.

00:14:21.940 --> 00:14:26.640
And then to put it all together, the setup function pulls the setup template and makes

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:31.979
a new file with the template, which contains other functions that can run through the analysis.

00:14:31.979 --> 00:14:36.940
And then when you run the function to query the data, it does so, and it does so chattily

00:14:36.940 --> 00:14:40.500
so that it's abstracting away the logic but making sure that you know where things are

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:42.380
saved.

00:14:42.380 --> 00:14:48.059
So I use don't repeat yourself and talk to yourself by cleaning up code with clear names

00:14:48.059 --> 00:14:49.059
and ordering.

00:14:49.179 --> 00:14:53.099
I made functions, and I made them chatty to communicate what they were doing.

00:14:53.099 --> 00:14:56.900
I made automated templates, and I made them prescriptive to help me know what to do year

00:14:56.900 --> 00:14:58.099
after year.

00:14:58.099 --> 00:15:01.419
And then I made a package to put it all together.

00:15:01.419 --> 00:15:07.340
And using this form of repeated reporting in R, I had a project that was reproducible,

00:15:07.340 --> 00:15:12.380
easy to keep track of, it had minimal manual work, was easily repeatable, and it freed

00:15:12.380 --> 00:15:17.659
up time, which I spent making other R packages.

00:15:17.659 --> 00:15:21.979
So my takeaway to you is that if you have a repetitive task that you find confusing

00:15:21.979 --> 00:15:26.419
and you're doing the same work over and over, abstract away or automate what you can and

00:15:26.419 --> 00:15:28.340
loudly communicate the rest.

00:15:28.340 --> 00:15:32.099
Or because it's catchier, don't repeat yourself, talk to yourself.

00:15:32.099 --> 00:15:33.099
Thank you.

00:15:33.099 --> 00:15:47.820
We have a few questions on Slido already.

00:15:47.820 --> 00:15:52.500
If anyone wants to ask questions, they're there in track number two.

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:57.260
The first one is how do you name your script if your boss asks you to double check something

00:15:57.260 --> 00:16:03.419
and you end up with another script that doesn't fit into the 0.1, 0.2 workflow?

00:16:03.419 --> 00:16:07.059
I would say if things are not going to stay the same year after year, something besides

00:16:07.059 --> 00:16:11.260
that, maybe make a folder that has extra things.

00:16:11.260 --> 00:16:13.979
The nice thing with this is that it gives you a fresh copy of the directory, which you

00:16:13.979 --> 00:16:18.739
can use, but you can always add things to that.

00:16:18.739 --> 00:16:23.739
Another question was as a person who's never made a package before, how do you make your

00:16:23.739 --> 00:16:29.260
package available to someone else within your organization without making it public?

00:16:29.260 --> 00:16:34.539
So if your organization is small, you can have a free Git repo that you can have up

00:16:34.539 --> 00:16:37.500
to three contributors in, so that's a good option.

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:44.419
I think if you have another form of version control at your work or if you have a network

00:16:44.419 --> 00:16:47.460
drive, you can install a package from there, even sending them the source code and they

00:16:47.460 --> 00:16:49.659
can install it using that.

00:16:49.659 --> 00:16:55.219
I know sending the source code is kind of not the point, but it's possible.

00:16:55.219 --> 00:17:02.099
What are the advantages of usethis, this UI info function, over a simple print call?

00:17:02.099 --> 00:17:07.619
I like the little icons that come with usethis, so there's like a – no, they communicate

00:17:07.619 --> 00:17:09.900
useful information, right?

00:17:09.900 --> 00:17:13.420
There's a little red dot that might indicate you need to do something, or there's a check

00:17:13.420 --> 00:17:16.020
mark that says this is where it is and this is where it's done.

00:17:16.020 --> 00:17:18.939
It's just a friendlier form of communicating, I think.

00:17:18.939 --> 00:17:24.099
Coming off of icons, someone asked, where are your icon and picture people from?

00:17:24.099 --> 00:17:25.099
My what?

00:17:25.099 --> 00:17:29.579
The icons and picture people that you use in the first team.

00:17:29.579 --> 00:17:30.660
The artist is here.

00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:36.020
I went to Vecteezy and this person had like 400 businessman images, so I chose one for

00:17:36.020 --> 00:17:37.020
every emotion.

00:17:37.020 --> 00:17:43.020
I had to cut some, but there's a lot.

00:17:43.020 --> 00:17:49.020
We have a few more minutes for questions, so can you estimate the time trade-off?

00:17:49.020 --> 00:17:52.380
That is, how much additional time did you spend and how much time did you save in the

00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:55.619
long run?

00:17:55.619 --> 00:18:00.939
I've done a few iterations of this, and it does take some time investment up front, for

00:18:00.939 --> 00:18:02.459
sure.

00:18:02.459 --> 00:18:09.300
As for the long run, I quit my job, so you'll have to ask my coworker Charlene how much

00:18:09.300 --> 00:18:10.300
time it saves.

00:18:11.060 --> 00:18:14.939
Going through these projects was back and forth that sometimes took many, many months

00:18:14.939 --> 00:18:16.939
of checking assumptions.

00:18:16.939 --> 00:18:22.099
Even if you have to do that, I think it's a time investment in the long run.

00:18:22.099 --> 00:18:27.540
Someone else asked, a lot of your recommendations seem to be software engineering principles.

00:18:27.540 --> 00:18:32.339
Would you recommend that our users have a formal education in this field to prevent

00:18:32.339 --> 00:18:33.339
some troubles?

00:18:33.339 --> 00:18:34.339
No.

00:18:34.339 --> 00:18:37.660
I have no training in software engineering at all.

00:18:37.660 --> 00:18:47.420
Everything I know is from Jenny Bryan, so I think you're all fine.

00:18:47.420 --> 00:18:50.819
Did you get pushback when initially transitioning to this workflow?

00:18:50.819 --> 00:18:56.540
If so, how did you convince them that this method may be better?

00:18:56.540 --> 00:19:02.780
I think there's always pushback for these kind of things, but if someone is in a position

00:19:02.780 --> 00:19:07.300
like your boss where they want to advance and they don't want you to have to waste your

00:19:07.300 --> 00:19:10.780
time doing the same thing over and over again, I think there's an argument to be made.

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:14.579
I think it's a lot easier to keep people at a job if they're happy and doing work that

00:19:14.579 --> 00:19:19.099
they're interested in rather than copy and pasting things over and over again.

00:19:19.099 --> 00:19:25.260
But I don't have a good answer on pushback.

00:19:25.260 --> 00:19:28.660
We have a lot of questions here, so I may share them with you after in case we don't

00:19:28.660 --> 00:19:31.979
answer them all.

00:19:31.979 --> 00:19:36.619
One most recent one is, what is the name of your package?

00:19:36.819 --> 00:19:38.819
This package?

00:19:38.819 --> 00:19:42.459
The one that you created internally.

00:19:42.459 --> 00:19:47.579
So we had one called R-CNO, the organization was called CNO, so you just put R before it,

00:19:47.579 --> 00:19:52.060
and then we had a report, obviously.

00:19:52.060 --> 00:19:56.540
We had a report on exams that we wrote, so the package was just called Exams Report.

00:19:56.540 --> 00:20:03.500
I think as long as you don't name it like dplyr, you're likely not to have any conflicts.

00:20:03.500 --> 00:20:06.500
I think we have time for two more.

00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:10.459
One is, the hardest thing with this approach seems to be maintenance and sustaining.

00:20:10.459 --> 00:20:15.660
Can you speak to that side of package development and functionalizing?

00:20:15.660 --> 00:20:20.459
I think for this, it wasn't as much of an issue because things were so similar year

00:20:20.459 --> 00:20:21.459
after year.

00:20:21.459 --> 00:20:26.900
Like, the point was kind of that things never changed, so you wanted to, like, abstract

00:20:26.900 --> 00:20:30.579
those things away because it was not useful going through the same thing over and over

00:20:30.579 --> 00:20:31.579
again.

00:20:31.579 --> 00:20:35.380
So I think for maintaining, I did not cover it at all, but writing tests for your package

00:20:35.380 --> 00:20:39.500
is a really big thing, so if things are changing in your data or in your code or things that

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:43.219
you're getting, being able to keep track of those.

00:20:43.219 --> 00:20:48.699
And then the last question is asking about what you use for version control.

00:20:48.699 --> 00:20:49.699
I use Git.

00:20:49.699 --> 00:20:50.699
Yeah.

00:20:50.699 --> 00:20:53.699
Well, thank you very much.

00:21:01.579 --> 00:21:02.579
Thank you.

00:21:02.579 --> 00:21:02.579


